In languages with ternary I would do this (I agree with Go's decision to remove it but in a case this simple, I'd use it if it were there)<p><pre><code>  int hello() {
    return cond ? 0 : 1
  }
</code></pre>
In Go, I'd do this, but then I seem to like named return values more than most Go programmers...<p><pre><code>  func hello() (res int) {
        if !cond {
            res = 1
        }
        return
    }
</code></pre>
Of course, coming from C/C++, it would have to be an extremely special case for me to have logic where "true" mapped to 0 and "false" mapped to 1, because that just seems wacky.

The reason I don't like this way is it can be harder to refactor. You don't want "return 1" happening if cond. For example, if you refactor to something like this:<p><pre><code>    func hello() int {
       var result int
       if cond {
          result = 0
       }
       result = 1

       // New code with result

       return result
    }

</code></pre>
Now, in this case, you don't want result to be 1 if cond, so you have to add the else condition. If you start with if-else, this is less likely to bit you in the future.<p>This particular bug just bit me in a bad way in production because I had what you have and and to make an quick production fix and did a refactor just like this and missed adding the else.
